{"author":{"id":"8e1777f58c0cfe5478428be8f9fcbfe90d25e44689578335da8fc2246fe0915a"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1452342770,"nonce":"sx1Y+3NeNHxUL9Q6do4BkPl5Qd0=","metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDE3MDIzNDA2OQ==","github-url":"https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/issues/522#issuecomment-170234069"},"message":"\u003e \u003e unlikely to get them into the main channel\n\u003e \n\u003e I don't see this as a problem, we should have our own galaxy channel which we dump all of the old crap into that no one (i.e. bioconda, r) wants to deal with. We can have as strict of versions as we want.\n\nWe can do this. But we need to get all on board I guess and integrate it deeply with bioaRchigve and cargo-port.\n\n\u003e \u003e Anaconda repositories are limited in space \n\u003e \n\u003e self hosting is easy. We could do it on depot. I'd say we _start_ self hosting, and not even think about anaconda's official ones. We should be _able_ to create conda packages for all of bioarchive automatically, not worrying about running out of space. (Of course, we should not, just the ones that are actually useful)\n\nHehe, see here: \"If conda can handle such cases I guess it would be easier for us to integrate this directly into bioaRchive instead of doing this on demand on pushing regularly to bioconda.\" from https://github.com/bioconda/bioconda-recipes/pull/574#issuecomment-170072824 :)\n\n\u003e \u003e I really had hoped to get our stuff in bioconda and join forces here \n\u003e \n\u003e will it be any easier going forward? With new packages? Or do they really not care about strict versioning?\n\nThey are not really aware of the problem I guess. Or we are just to radical.\nWe have a lot of binaries, e.g starforge can be more or less replaced by conda if we do it right and at least this can/should be shared with bioconda. In the end it does not matter if we activate 3 or 4 channels by default. What I really like to avoid is to just recreate recipes because we have a more strict police. \n\n@mvdbeek \n\n\u003e This looks super-interesting and the build-tests will be a huge win!\n\u003e I guess the only step forward is trying, if you think that conda is as close to feaure-complete as it gets.\n\u003e - Will we be able to support packages by different owners? (Or is this concept obsolete now?)\n\nThis concept is obsolete know and is replaced by channels. Channels do fit the IUC group and you can move recipes between channels without any hassle. So if one channel disappears we should be able to create a new one and put all recipes back in.\n- Would this require users to setup their own channel? \n\nYes, or contribute to the IUC, bioconda channel. I would vote for collecting recipes (as we do now) in one channel.\n- What would be the procedure to quickly test a new conda recipe?\n\nAssuming you have defined tests ...\n\n```\nconda build bowtie2\n```\n\n\u003e I like the fact that every tool developer has easy and (kind of) unlimited access to the toolshed, so I think we should be aiming for a similar resource to keep the transitioning barrier low.\n\nHehe, unlimited it is only because the Galaxy project is paying. Bioconda is now depended on continuum and has 100GB afaik - and this is a special offer usually you get 3GB.\n\n\u003e Maybe some of the points will be clear once I tried the new stuff.\n\u003e Also in-the-face docs would be good, I have certainly read @gregvonkuster [blog entry](http://gregvonkuster.org/galaxy-tool-shed-framework-building-galaxy-tools/) tens of times.\n\nI'm volunteering to write such things and include it into the best practice IUC repository as soon as it is more clear how do we want to proceed here. A dedicated hackathon would be also nice. Most of my porting time is spend in compiling and writing tests, so I could need help here :)\n\nThat said this is not super urgent as we can only rely on conda builds if Galaxy 16.01 is on most installations, but we could work the infrastructure behind this in the meantime and get some Docker-Conda only containers running :)","files":null}]}